    <item>
      <title>Exploring a Quiet Morning in the City</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/post-testing/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 28 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/post-testing/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://i.pinimg.com/736x/97/5b/e4/975be4e103206734e03e332bcbc4c7be.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Full-Size mornings&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;a-quiet-morning-in-the-city&#34;&gt;A Quiet Morning in the City&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It was one of those mornings where the light felt soft and deliberate, not harsh like the usual noon sun. The streets were still half‑empty, and the air carried a faint smell of coffee and fresh bread.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Everything moved slower, and for once it felt okay not to rush.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-light-through-the-windows&#34;&gt;The Light Through the Windows&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;As the sun rose higher, the light began to cut through the windows of old brick buildings. The narrow alleys turned into long lines of gold and shadow, and every parked bike, every window frame, every cracked wall suddenly had a role in the scene.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
